abstract: >-
  A personal essay collection and structured knowledge graph mapping the three
  major Buddhist Abhidharma traditions (Theravāda, Sarvāstivāda, Yogācāra) onto
  contemporary frameworks in computational phenomenology — predictive processing,
  active inference, Global Workspace Theory, Parallel Distributed Processing, and
  related approaches. Comprises sixteen essays (eight themes × English + Japanese), a
  cross-tradition dharma comparison table (~130 dharmas across nine sheets), and
  a JSON-LD knowledge graph (307 nodes, schema.org + custom vocabulary) with
  bilingual labels and Sanskrit / Pāli / Chinese philological alignment. An
  interactive 2D/3D viewer is provided. v0.4.0 adds Theme 8 (Epistemic luck
  across traditions) — starting from the finding that the Free Energy Principle
  (FEP) literature never engages with the Gettier problem (justified true belief
  that is true only by luck, and so not knowledge), it turns to Dharmakīrti's
  pramāṇa-vāda (avisaṃvāda, arthakriyā) and its commentator Dharmottara (c. 770
  CE), who rejected a mirage/water case as invalid cognition roughly 1200 years
  before Gettier. Deliberately avoids the "Buddhism had the answer first"
  framing. Developed in collaboration with the Claude
  language model (Anthropic) for synthesis, cross-tradition mapping, and graph
  encoding; the author retains responsibility for all claims.
